Identify the ten major sites of drug action in the CNS
(1) {{c1::Action potential in presynaptic fiber }}
(2) {{c2::synthesis of transmitter}} 
(3) {{c3::storage }}
(4) {{c4::metabolism}}
(5) {{c5::release }}
(6) {{c6::reuptake into the nerve ending or uptake into a glial cell }}
(7) {{c7::degradation}}
(8) {{c8::receptor for the transmitter }}
(9) {{c9::receptor-induced increase or decrease in ionic conductance }}
(10) {{c10::retrograde signaling}}

SLO 1

Identify major types of neurotransmitters; describe their basic molecular and physiologic functions in the CNS

1. Peptides-including {{c8::Amino acids and biogenic amines}}
a. {{c9::Amino acids}} are the the primary excitatory ({{c10::glutamate and aspartate)}} and inhibitory ({{c11::glycine and γ-aminobutyric acid}}) neurotransmitters in the CNS. This category also includes {{c12::endogenous opioids (endorphins and enkephalins)}},{{c13:: tachykinins – Substance P, and MANY others (glucagon, ADH, etc.)}}
2. {{c14::Biogenic amines}} are the primary {{c15::modulatory}} neurotransmitters in the CNS. These include {{c1::dopamine, norepinephrine, and epinephrine}} which share a common {{c2::catechol}} group; {{c3::histamine}} has an imidazole group; and {{c4::serotonin}} has an indole group. 
2. {{c16::Endocannabinoids}}
•{{c17::Endogenous cannabinoids}} that activate cannabinoid receptors
•{{c18::Arachidonic-acid derivatives (lipids)}}
3.?{{c5::Acetylcholine (a neurotransmitter in diffuse modulatory systems in the CNS)}}, {{c6::adenosine,}} and {{c7::nitric oxide (NO)}} do not fall into either structural category.
What does the blood brain barrier do?

Protects the brain from toxic substances
-NTs such as Epi, NE, DA, and glutamate would wreak havoc if allowed access to the CNS when released in the periphery
Which chemical characteristics would facilitate or impede penetration of the blood-brain barrier?

Regarding the blood brain barrier, there is a correlation between the {{c1::oil/water partition}} coefficient of a compound and its {{c2::ability to enter the brain from the systemic circulation.}}
Specific transporters facilitate the entry into the brain of certain compounds (squares), such as glucose (glucose transporter) and L-DOP{{c3::A (large neutral L-amino acid transporter).}} Transporters also pump certain compounds out of the CNS (diamonds), such as {{c4::phenobarbital and phenytoin}}

Martha P is a 66-year-old woman with a 4-year history of worsening Parkinson’s disease, a neurological disorder resulting from the progressive degeneration of nigrostriatal neurons that use dopamine as a neurotransmitter. The disease causes a resting tremor, rigidity, difficulty initiating movement, and postural instability. Ms. P takes Sinemet, which contains levodopa and carbidopa.
1.Why is levodopa used in the treatment of Parkinson’s disease, and what is the relationship of this compound to dopamine?
2.Why does Sinemet contain both levodopa and carbidopa?

patient presents for evaluation following diagnosis of substance use disorder. He has been using cocaine habitually for two years and wants to begin a journey of recovery. Which neurotransmitter and site of action, as indicated in the image, is associated with this drug’s abuse potential?
A.Dopamine, site 5
B.Dopamine, site 6
C.Norepinephrine, site 2
D.Norepinephrine, site 7
E.Serotonin, site 4
F.Serotonin, site 8

Which antidepressant inhibits serotonin neurotransmission at site 4 in the image and is rarely prescribed as first-line therapy due to high risk of interactions with both foods and other pharmacotherapies?
A.Amitriptyline
B.Bupropion
C.Paroxetine
D.Selegiline
E.Duloxetine

Which neurotransmitter and ion current pair mediates the majority of excitatory neurotransmission in the central nervous system?
A.GABA; Cl- efflux
B.GABA; Cl- influx
C.Serotonin; K+ efflux
D.Serotonin; K+ influx
E.Glutamate; Na+ efflux
F.Glutamate; Na+ influx

A patient suffering from major depressive disorder presents for follow-up. It has been 4 weeks since he began the prescribed pharmacotherapy. His depressive symptoms have improved but he is experiencing intolerable loss of libido and asks if he can switch to a different medication. He mentions that he also wants to quit smoking. Which agent may be a good option at this time?
A.Citalopram
B.Bupropion
C.Fluoxetine
D.Sertraline
E.Venlafaxine

A 41 y/o female suffering from insomnia is prescribed a drug that enhances production of fast inhibitory postsynaptic potentials by hyperpolarizing neuronal cell membranes. Activation of which receptor type most likely mediates the therapeutic effect of the drug?
A.Ionotropic glutamate receptors
B.Metabotropic glutamate receptors
C.Ionotropic GABA receptors
D.Metabotropic GABA receptors
E.Ionotropic serotonin receptors
F.Metabotropic serotonin receptors

The blood-brain barrier is characterized by ___________ between capillary endothelial cells. As a result, drugs that lack a specific transporter must be highly _____________ in order to penetrate the central nervous system.
A.fenestrations; lipophilic
B.fenestrations; hydrophilic
C.tight junctions; hydrophobic
D.tight junctions; hydrophilic
E.gap junctions; lipophilic
F.gap junctions; hydrophobic
